                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Personally I use one of those nifty little Timers from Eqinterface &lt;don't remember the name specifically that I used&gt; but it let me set up several timers <use 4 but you can use up to 8 I think> which I use for Haste, charm, and 2 seperate mez timers.  Those are only good for XP groups though and it's easy to keep up with.  
<br />
Raids are another story.  The most effective way I have seen to date IMHO is setting up a buff channel for the raid.  1 or 2 people of each buffing class are assigned to be in the channel at the begining of the raid.  We rotated the people assigned to keep from getting bored.  When a person dies or looses buff, he/she knows to pop in channel and ask for the specific buff needed.  Once the buff is recieved, they leave the room.  This method does several things.  1. Cuts down on raid channel Spam.  2. Makes it so mana is not wasted by say 2 enchanters responding to a request for haste at the same time.  3.  Making a dedicated buffer makes it less likely a person will need to ask repeatedly for the buffs required. 
<br />
There are other systems out there, but I like this one the best that I have seen so far.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=775907" target="_blank" class="postlink">Mistofelees MagikCat</a>
<br />
65 Enchanter
<br />
Cazic-Thule</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
