                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Mistofelees wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The most effective way I have seen to date IMHO is setting up a buff channel for the raid.  1 or 2 people of each buffing class are assigned to be in the channel at the begining of the raid.  We rotated the people assigned to keep from getting bored.  When a person dies or looses buff, he/she knows to pop in channel and ask for the specific buff needed.  Once the buff is recieved, they leave the room.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is exactly what we do as well. Its a super system. People who are new to raiding with us are usually surprised at how quickly we get ressed people buffed back up, including any special requests (such as 9s & symbol rather than virtue).  All a person needs to do is join the channel after they die and mention it there, and consent the raid (on test server) or the CR folks. Once they are all set up they leave the channel.
<br />

<br />
When we get several people asking for VoQ or haste (or if a lot of people died recently), we MGB it.
<br />

<br />
It also gives me notice of who all died, and when they got ressed. That usually gives me time to see which group they are in, and who else is in the group who also is getting a res. Fairly often I am able to buff them both rather than individually.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
